m like an obvious default for many businesses and organizations but for those months when only a few events are planned it can mean a rather sparse looking calendar, and empty calendars have a way of implying low organizational activity, not the most desirable impression you want to leave with your website visitors.</p>\n<p>For that reason one of the  things we champion here at Timely is the idea of the<a href="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/Screen-Shot-2012-08-28-at-1.17.42-PM.png"><img class="alignright size-medium wp-image-8675" title="Screen Shot 2012-08-28 at 1.17.42 PM" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/Screen-Shot-2012-08-28-at-1.17.42-PM-300x221.png" alt="" width="300" height="221" /></a> &#8220;Curated Calendar.&#8221; Over the last few years the internet has taken on an interesting new dynamic. As the information available online has exploded, a new social layer has been necessary to sift through the content (news, blogs, photos, videos etc) and separate the wheat from the chaff so to speak. This has given rise to a practice known as <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Media_curation">content curation</a>, usually dedicated <a href="http://www.brainpickings.org/">individuals</a> and sometimes whole <a href="http://flavorpill.com/newyork">companies</a> motivated by a mandate to filter and serve only the best of the best information on a certain topic or interest. When you curate content and you do it well, it can become a powerful brand marketing strategy as it builds you a reputation as a trusted and desirable source for top quality information on a certain topic, and if you can save people time and effort searching through all the choice the web offers them you&#8217;ll quickly develop a loyal following.</p>\n<p>Curating event content is just as important. Let&#8217;s say you&#8217;re a fundraising organization for cancer research, and you have 10 big fundraising events each year, galas, marathons, auctions etc. Spreading those events out over a 12 month/365 day calendar may leave you with a fairly empty looking events schedule month to month but if you also seek out relatable events you could fill your calendar with a diverse range of interesting and valuable opportunities for your members. For example: talks from <a href="http://www.ted.com/talks/jay_bradner_open_source_cancer_research.html">cancer researchers</a>, local or international <a href="http://www.worldcancercongress.org/">medical conferences</a>, book launches, <a href="http://www.webmd.com/prostate-cancer/features/fifty-years-of-milestones-in-cancer-research">research milestones</a>, member get-togethers- a whole range of event experiences that may not be directly tied to the organization itself yet would still enrich the learning and development of your members. Your members will seek out your calendar not only because of your events but also because they&#8217;ll recognize it as the definitive calendar for all events related to cancer research.</p>\n<p><img class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-8671" title="Screen Shot 2012-08-28 at 12.21.20 PM" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/Screen-Shot-2012-08-28-at-12.21.20-PM-300x168.png" alt="" width="300" height="168" /></p>\n<p>Obviously one daunting task of populating a calendar with outside events is the extra work it would require for administrators, and that&#8217;s where a little &#8220;machine curation&#8221; can come in handy. With Timely&#8217;s All-in-One Event Calendar we&#8217;ve taken a lot of the leg work out of populating your calendar by making it really easy to syndicate and subscribe to calendar feeds from other calendars, even non-Ai1EC&#8217;s. This means that when you find a complimentary events calendar you love, you can easily <a href="http://help.time.ly/customer/portal/articles/504373-how-do-i-import-a-calendar-from-outlook-google-calendar-ical-">subscribe to the .ics feed</a> and add it to your Ai1EC&#8217;s Calendar Feeds, tagging it and categorizing it as you desire.</p>\n<p>The events from the calendars you subscribe to are then fed into your calendar on a daily basis, maintaining all their information and formatting. You have thus provided a curated feed of relatable events to your calendar visitors and organization members with a simple one time set-up that will fill your calendar with fresh event content as it&#8217;s posted by the event publisher.</p>\n<h3>Here are 6 tips for creating a great curated events calendar:</h3>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Think outside the typical &#8220;Event&#8221; definition &#8211; </strong>events could come from anywhere, they could be international or local, they could be attendance events or simply notable anniversaries or occasions that relate to your industry. Don&#8217;t get trapped in the typical &#8220;local event&#8221; model.</li>\n<li><strong>Make connections with sister organizations,</strong> share your events with theirs and vice versa.</li>\n<li><strong>Check the calendars of notable speakers, authors or personalities &#8211; </strong>seek out the notable individuals who relate to your brand  and subscribe to their calendar feeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Aggregate event feeds from local news media and tourism event calendars </strong>- They may not all be on the .ics format but if they are you can easily grab individual events or entire calendars into your Ai1EC.</li>\n<li><strong>Allow community event submissions</strong> &#8211; The All-in-One can be set up to allow community members to post their own events (with moderator review) a great way of gathering event content from your very own community</li>\n<li><strong>Subscribe to member calendars</strong> &#8211; If other members in your organization host events and feature them on event calendars (Ai1EC or otherwise) you can have their events feed into your calendar.</li>\n</ol>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a: